The fair spinner shown is spun once. What is the probability of spinning an odd number? Express your answer as a common fraction.

[asy]
dot((0,0));

draw((3,0)--(3,3)--(0,3));
import graph;
draw(Circle((0,0),25));
draw((0,-25)--(0,25));
draw((0,0)--(25,0));
draw((0,0)--(-15,9),Arrow);
label("15",(-10,0),W);
label("23",(10,10),NE);
label("14",(10,-10),SE);
[/asy]

content.solution_latex:
We can use Pascal's identity $ \binom{n-1}{k-1}+\binom{n-1}{k}=\binom{n}{k}$ to find $\binom{15}{9}$.

\begin{align*}
\binom{15}{8}+\binom{15}{9}&=\binom{16}{9} \rightarrow \\
6435+\binom{15}{9}&=11440 \rightarrow \\
\binom{15}{9}&=5005
\end{align*}

We can use the identity again to find $\binom{15}{10}$.

\begin{align*}
\binom{15}{9}+\binom{15}{10}&=\binom{16}{10} \rightarrow \\
5005+\binom{15}{10}&=8008 \rightarrow \\
\binom{15}{10}&=3003
\end{align*}

Therefore, $\binom{15}{10}=\boxed{3003}$.

